Anonymous Thu 29 Oct 2020 08:58:51 No.33708671 Report
Quoted By: >>33708785 >>33709313
>>33708054
Since I have a setting that fits your second option, I'll give you a few more things to chew on.

Choose how your world works right now.
This does not mean choosing between the options you listed. I saying you need to know the whys & hows of your world before populating it. The following questions may not be relevant for you, but give you an idea how I built mine.
How logical is it, ie are you planning to be more like a Harry Potter or a Sherlock Holmes?
How did the anthros come about, and how integrated are they with humans? And continuing that, how many racial/ethnic groups do they have? What percentage of each exist, and where are the anthros the majority? Think in broad, sweeping terms first.
What disadvantages do they have? In mine, humans have the weakest sense of smell. The anthros are better there but are far weaker than their feral counterparts. On the other hand, humans have better sight. They evolved three color sight first, and have better ability to resolve that in daylight. The anthros have fur, but humans have higher quantities of subcutaneous body fat and better thermoregulation. Humans already had a more advanced shoulder musculature, with all that entails.
Society: Since my anthros evolved around the same period of history as humans, as pockets of anthros & humans encountered each other - what happened? Since my setting is closer to an alternate history than a GW kind of history, I put myself in the hole of a large backstory. So I could say that the reason the Romans found Europe increasingly hostile as they went north was that anthro species played them against the regional humans. Yet they also traded more willingly with the Romans for then current tech. When the Church spread north...

If I want a more alien feel to the anthros for a given story, I'd start further back in history. One set in 2000 BCE will be far more unsubtle than in 2000 CE.
But they're still a society with the same needs as humans.

Anonymous Thu 29 Oct 2020 09:35:26 No.33708891 Report
Quoted By:
>>33708054
It really depends on what you're doing and its flavor. The first category crops up because we all have a deal with each other that we expect animal women in our stories, so you can just go "and she was a cat", and we'll all get it. But that sort of thing doesn't really fly in a larger setting, because it breaks suspension of disbelief, so they'll go "and she was a Khajiit/Caitian/Chanurr/some other type of meow-sayer" with that still mostly just coming down to that writer's definition of a cat person in fiction.

I'm guessing the biggest difference is that there being a different for people, but with animal features, that really identifies them as a separate species, is that it implies that there's a larger cultural difference between them and humans, and that they developed separately for a period of time. When they don't have a cultural name, and it's just animal person this, animal person that, it's usually also implied they were always part of the same society as humans.

>>33708785
You really don't have to worry about the stealing. Even if you had my notes, which range to a few hundreds typescript pages, you'd end up with a completely different story.
As an example, my canids & humans aren't close but co-exist in various ways. In some measure, the canids don't like our domestication of wolves. It was one of the lynchpins to establishing communication, but humans would have the position they do without dogs. The canids did it without so some still have that evolutionary chip on the shoulder.
Yet in another setting I have, the canids are far more clingy (modeled off of domestic dogs) when they aren't standoffish (modeled on wolves). Interbreeding is possible, unlike the other setting, but there's some rather unfortunate consequences.

You might want to do a good bit of reading on lab rats and immunology. Humans are rather hardy & adaptable, but in a different way. I've found that there's a lot of material to be mined past the gristle most mainstream media uses. As an example, we learned how to give sub-Q injections on the old male lab rats. The girls? Looking at them wrong risked a nasty bite & several pages of accident paperwork.

>>33708054
I generally think second is better, though it requires serious investment of thought and planning for the world and everything in it. It gives much more distinct and interesting cultures, conflicts, societies, and potential choices. Despite that I think it's still better to have a fair degree of size equalization, like the really small species maybe averaging in the four foot range with the really big species being mid seven foot, so that you don't need Disney magic to make the world work like in Zootopia. You also really need to know each species strengths and weaknesses, at least for the ones that are going to play a major role, like with humans being poor swimmers, speed runners, not having a Jacobson's organ (which is what allows animals to "communicate" with smells, like during mating), the hearing range of humans (especially important to take into account when regarding animals like mice which have a large amount of verbal communication done outside our hearing range), and menstruation being present almost exclusively in humans and bats.

More people were putting up a second structure directly adjacent to it, nail guns blasting and welders sparking while everybody crowded around to see how it was coming along. Far back on the right was a tent city made up of several rows that I could see, families milling about and chatting like everything was fine and today was just another ordinary day in the neighborhood.

>Nobody looked all that unhappy. I could see the wear and tear on their faces and in how they walked or talked, but the overall atmosphere seemed...hopeful. Maybe even happy. Which made sense; the war had just been won, things were looking up. But despite the haphazard living arrangements, despite dirty, ragged clothing and rationed food -- people seemed happy.

We are approaching the home stretch. I would hazard a guess at between 3 and 5 chapters remain depending on how I slice it. As usual, tell me what you think, good or bad, I don't care. I always read any feedback.
